<HEADLINE>
<P>
NONFICTION IN BRIEF: HUSBAND IS THE PAST TENSE OF DADDY AND OTHER DISPATCHES 
FROM THE FRONT LINES OF MOTHERHOOD BY TERYL ZARNOW (ADDISON-WESLEY: $15.95; 221 
PP.) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Sonja Bolle 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The title of Teryl Zarnow's collection, published in time for Mother's Day, 
speaks for itself. 
</P>
<P>
These pieces from her syndicated Knight-Ridder column, "Color Me Mommy," 
maintain a humorous character while serving up the undercurrent of 
self-conscious "what have I done?" lament popular in the new genre of parenting 
literature. When Zarnow writes, "Rules have civilized us; they have created 
order out of chaos. I am Ayatollah the Mommy; my rulings come swift and 
merciless," the reader can be sure there are some laughs in this collection 
that will be appreciated only by those whose normal sleeping patterns have been 
irretrievably disturbed by night feedings. Sonja Bolle 
</P>
</TEXT>
