<HEADLINE>
<P>
POP FACES: CHADWICK'S 'HOUSE': IS THIS BLASPHEMY? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE HOCHMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A lot of rock music has been termed blasphemous, though rarely by the people 
who created it. 
</P>
<P>
But that's the term used by Guy Chadwick, singer-songwriter of the English 
quartet House of Love, to describe his use of religious imagery in several 
songs on the band's new album, "House of Love." The group will be at the Roxy 
on June 15 and 16. 
</P>
<P>
"I don't mean to be blasphemous," the sunken-cheeked Chadwick, 30, said 
recently over a beer in the bar of a West Hollywood hotel. "But I'm sort of 
challenging my own beliefs. I don't know how I feel about religion or God. The 
power of religion has always interested me, and to an extent I'm flirting with 
it in a dangerous way. I do sometimes think, 'God, should I write that? Will He 
let me get away with that?' " 
</P>
<P>
The truth is, Chadwick's references to Jesus and God are most often ambiguous 
and ambivalent, and at worst questioning. His attitude, he says, was shaped by 
his upbringing, in which, after spending his first two years in Germany where 
his father was stationed with the British Army, he was exposed to a colorful 
world of wonders first in Singapore and then Malaya. But at age 13 he found 
himself stuck in a relatively drab boarding school in the English Midlands. 
</P>
<P>
"It was dreary, and in some ways affected me," he said. "I remember being 
disappointed in my adolescence -- a particularly bad hand dealt me, moving from 
somewhere like (Asia) to such a boring place." 
</P>
<P>
Then in the late '80s, the flowering punk scene turned his head. "It literally 
made me pick up a guitar and learn to play," he said. "It was really that 
corny." 
</P>
<P>
After several years of struggling to get a foothold in music, Chadwick signed 
an ill-fated solo deal with RCA in England in 1983. Then four years ago he 
formed House of Love, which released an independent album in 1988, drawing 
critical praise for its brisk, thoughtful guitar-pop. The new album, with a 
sound that harks back both to punk and '60s pop in a manner somewhat akin to 
that of the Church or the Stone Roses, has won even greater accolades in the 
British rock press. 
</P>
<P>
Some rock fans may consider Chadwick's biggest blasphemy to be a song on the 
new album titled "Beatles and Stones," in which he sings, "The Beatles and the 
Stones / Made it good to be alone," countering the communal-spirit party line 
associated with those groups' music. 
</P>
<P>
"If anything, that song's reverent," Chadwick maintained. "I vaguely remember 
seeing Jimi Hendrix on 'Top of the Pops,' " he said. "And I barely remember the 
Beatles." 
</P>
<P>
And he readily acknowledges ambitions that are far from Beatlesque. Instead, he 
admires the accomplishments of the Only Ones, a late-'70s English band greatly 
loved by those who remember it, but remembered by few. 
</P>
<P>
"At least they made some records, left something behind," Chadwick said. "It 
wasn't all in vain. They left something and got something as well." STEVE 
HOCHMAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Guy Chadwick: "I don't mean to be blasphemous. But I'm sort of 
challenging my own beliefs." MINDY SCHAUER 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
